I welcome ideas.

271
00:15:43,443 --> 00:15:45,360
I like to see
hard work rewarded.

272
00:15:45,486 --> 00:15:48,530
It's a two-way street on my team.
Am I making myself clear?

273
00:15:50,033 --> 00:15:51,450
Yes, Katharine.

274
00:15:54,871 --> 00:15:55,871
And call me Katharine.

275
00:15:56,831 --> 00:15:57,998
O.K.

276
00:15:58,499 --> 00:16:00,334
So, let's get
to work, shall we?

277
00:16:01,419 --> 00:16:04,338
This department's profile
last year was damn pitiful.

278
00:16:04,464 --> 00:16:06,882
Our team has got
its work cut out for it.

279
00:16:08,718 --> 00:16:09,801
O.K., thanks.

280
00:16:12,305 --> 00:16:14,556
Damn! I forgot
my pills again!

281
00:16:16,184 --> 00:16:17,684
Did you hear about

282
00:16:17,769 --> 00:16:19,311
that shot they got
in Europe?

283
00:16:19,395 --> 00:16:22,230
They give it to
the women in their arm,

284
00:16:22,315 --> 00:16:23,982
and it's good
for five years.

285
00:16:24,067 --> 00:16:26,068
The damn pills,
I'm always forgetting them.

286
00:16:29,238 --> 00:16:31,657
- I thought you might like this.
- Oh, thank you.

287
00:16:34,911 --> 00:16:37,412
Tess, would you come in
and bring a notebook?

288
00:16:38,331 --> 00:16:40,791
They've sold off the paper
and printing divisions.

289
00:16:40,875 --> 00:16:43,794
They sell distribution too,
we're talking scorched earth.

290
00:16:44,545 --> 00:16:45,629
Come on in.

291
00:16:47,340 --> 00:16:49,925
Tess, this is Ginny.
Ginny, Tess.

292
00:16:52,553 --> 00:16:54,262
I'm throwing
a cocktail thing

293
00:16:54,347 --> 00:16:56,014
to introduce myself
to the department.

294
00:16:56,099 --> 00:16:57,307
Ginny has
some great ideas.

295
00:16:57,392 --> 00:16:58,475
Will you
jot them down?

296
00:16:58,559 --> 00:17:02,813
- Sure.
- The caterer is Acme Eats.

297
00:17:02,897 --> 00:17:04,439
You can get the number
from information.

298
00:17:04,524 --> 00:17:06,608
They do the usual
hors d'oeuvres and such.

299
00:17:06,693 --> 00:17:10,070
The Raging Bull
has a bartender service.

300
00:17:10,154 --> 00:17:13,573
The liquor store on Broadway
and Liberty delivers.

301
00:17:13,658 --> 00:17:15,033
Got that, Bess?

302
00:17:15,118 --> 00:17:18,286
Tess. Yeah, if that's the way
you want to go.

303
00:17:19,789 --> 00:17:20,997
You have another idea?

304
00:17:21,582 --> 00:17:24,584
I was reading in W
about dim sum,

305
00:17:24,669 --> 00:17:26,211
little Chinese
dumplings.

306
00:17:26,295 --> 00:17:28,004
A restaurant
on Mott Street

307
00:17:28,089 --> 00:17:29,339
does them for
cocktail parties.

308
00:17:30,049 --> 00:17:31,967
I just love
those little dumplings.

309
00:17:32,093 --> 00:17:33,176
It might be more fun

310
00:17:33,261 --> 00:17:34,511
than the usual tidbits.

311
00:17:34,595 --> 00:17:35,929
I have it on my desk.
I could get it.

312
00:17:36,013 --> 00:17:39,099
- You read W?
- I read a lot of things.

313
00:17:39,183 --> 00:17:41,810
You never know where big ideas
could come from.

314
00:17:42,437 --> 00:17:44,354
Well, I guess
you're right,

315
00:17:44,480 --> 00:17:46,773
if dumplings can be considered
a big idea.

316
00:17:48,526 --> 00:17:49,735
That ought to
get you started.

317
00:17:49,819 --> 00:17:51,653
Ginny, thank you
so much.

318
00:17:52,363 --> 00:17:54,614
- Back to the gold mines.
- Right.

319
00:17:55,116 --> 00:17:56,199
You'll set those up?

320
00:17:56,284 --> 00:17:57,284
Right away.

321
00:17:57,368 --> 00:17:58,410
Dim sum, Tess.

322
00:17:58,494 --> 00:18:00,495
I like it,
contribution-wise.

323
00:18:00,747 --> 00:18:01,955
Keep it up.

324
00:18:05,960 --> 00:18:07,919
The chief says,
"We will respect your wish.

325
00:18:08,004 --> 00:18:09,546
"We will give you
an honorable death.

326
00:18:09,630 --> 00:18:10,964
But first, Kiki."

327
00:18:12,925 --> 00:18:15,343
Excuse me.
Excuse me.

328
00:18:15,678 --> 00:18:16,720
Thank you.

329
00:18:16,804 --> 00:18:17,763
Dim sum?

330
00:18:17,847 --> 00:18:19,514
Uh, yes, yes, yes.

331
00:18:19,682 --> 00:18:21,433
Now, listen.
You work with him.

332
00:18:21,517 --> 00:18:22,768
Thank you.

333
00:18:23,519 --> 00:18:24,561
Keep with him.

334
00:18:24,937 --> 00:18:27,773
So come on, Katharine,
what do you say?

335
00:18:27,857 --> 00:18:29,649
Jim, the man who spends

336
00:18:29,734 --> 00:18:32,527
every weekend in August
glued to his desk

337
00:18:32,612 --> 00:18:35,614
knows I can't sneak out
of my own party.

338
00:18:36,616 --> 00:18:38,074
I'll tell you what,
though.

339
00:18:38,576 --> 00:18:41,328
Get me in on the Southeast Air
divestiture plan,

340
00:18:41,746 --> 00:18:43,455
I'll buy you a drink...

341
00:18:43,539 --> 00:18:46,166
a bottle of Crystal,
two straws.

342
00:18:47,293 --> 00:18:48,710
Deal?

343
00:18:48,878 --> 00:18:50,504
Okey-dokey.

344
00:18:51,214 --> 00:18:52,714
Dim sum?

345
00:18:52,799 --> 00:18:54,132
Hi.

346
00:18:54,217 --> 00:18:55,300
Thank you.

347
00:18:55,384 --> 00:18:56,635
What a slob.

348
00:18:56,719 --> 00:18:58,136
You were
so smooth with him.

349
00:18:58,221 --> 00:19:00,555
- I probably would have...
- Never burn bridges.

350
00:19:01,057 --> 00:19:02,224
Today's junior prick,

351
00:19:02,308 --> 00:19:04,142
tomorrow's senior partner.

352
00:19:04,227 --> 00:19:06,603
So how do you think
the party's going?

353
00:19:06,687 --> 00:19:08,230
Pretty well,
I think.

354
00:19:08,481 --> 00:19:10,357
Should I stop
serving now?

355
00:19:11,567 --> 00:19:13,235
Better make
one more round.

356
00:19:14,111 --> 00:19:16,822
I'd love to help you,
but you can't busy the quarterback

357
00:19:16,906 --> 00:19:18,156
with passing out
the Gatorade.

358
00:19:18,241 --> 00:19:20,700
Arnie, my hero,
you've come.

359
00:19:34,090 --> 00:19:35,507
Yeah?

360
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:41,054
Um, I have an idea, and you said
I could come to you.

361
00:19:41,597 --> 00:19:42,931
Shoot.

362
00:19:46,435 --> 00:19:48,603
Well, you know
how Trask Industries

363
00:19:48,688 --> 00:19:51,147
has been looking to
buy into broadcasting?

364
00:19:51,357 --> 00:19:53,149
Something about
the department is...

365
00:19:53,234 --> 00:19:54,276
Working on it. Yeah.

366
00:19:54,360 --> 00:19:55,527
I've been
following it myself,

367
00:19:55,611 --> 00:19:57,571
and I suddenly
thought, "Radio."

368
00:19:58,865 --> 00:20:01,032
Trask is looking
for television stations.

369
00:20:01,534 --> 00:20:03,535
Well, so is every Tom,
Dick and Harry.

370
00:20:03,619 --> 00:20:06,037
My idea is that they
get their feet wet in radio

371
00:20:06,122 --> 00:20:07,205
and build
from there.

372
00:20:07,290 --> 00:20:09,958
It's not as glamorous
as jumping into TV,

373
00:20:10,042 --> 00:20:13,336
but it's a solid start,
and there's more of them for sale.

374
00:20:14,046 --> 00:20:15,589
It would solve
Trask's problem

375
00:20:15,673 --> 00:20:18,216
with Japanese competitors
trying to take him over.

376
00:20:18,634 --> 00:20:20,552
FCC forbids
foreign ownership

377
00:20:20,636 --> 00:20:22,512
of radio
as well as TV.

378
00:20:26,309 --> 00:20:27,434
Interesting.

379
00:20:27,518 --> 00:20:31,354
You've been, um...
following this, you say?

380
00:20:31,898 --> 00:20:33,106
Yeah.

381
00:20:33,649 --> 00:20:35,191
No chance
you overheard it,

382
00:20:35,318 --> 00:20:37,819
say, um...
on the elevator?

383
00:20:38,446 --> 00:20:39,821
No. No way.

384
00:20:40,031 --> 00:20:41,156
Somewhere?

385
00:20:41,782 --> 00:20:42,824
It's my idea.

386
00:20:43,868 --> 00:20:45,660
Good. Good.

387
00:20:48,331 --> 00:20:49,581
Discuss it
with anyone else?

388
00:20:50,124 --> 00:20:51,708
Nope. You think that

389
00:20:51,792 --> 00:20:53,126
there's something
there?

390
00:20:54,337 --> 00:20:55,587
I'll think it through
for you.

391
00:20:55,671 --> 00:20:57,797
Leave me your notes.
I'll have a look-see.

392
00:20:58,549 --> 00:21:00,008
O.K.

393
00:21:00,843 --> 00:21:03,428
Uh... I've been trying
to get into the entree program.

394
00:21:03,512 --> 00:21:05,013
This would be
a big push.

395
00:21:05,097 --> 00:21:06,932
If anything happens...

396
00:21:07,016 --> 00:21:10,060
Absolutely, Tess.
Two-way street, remember?

397
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:13,188
Yeah. Thank you.

398
00:21:34,502 --> 00:21:36,628
It's just...
It's so exciting.

399
00:21:36,712 --> 00:21:38,880
I mean, she takes
me seriously.

400
00:21:39,215 --> 00:21:40,548
I think it's because...

401
00:21:40,633 --> 00:21:41,800
I know you hate
when I say this,

402
00:21:41,884 --> 00:21:43,969
but I think it's because
she's a woman.

403
00:21:44,553 --> 00:21:47,597
There's none of that
chasing-around-the-desk crap.

404
00:21:47,682 --> 00:21:51,893
It's like she wants to be my mentor,
which is what I needed.

405
00:21:52,019 --> 00:21:54,813
I feel like I'm finally
getting somewhere, Mick.

406
00:21:54,897 --> 00:21:56,523
Tess, that's great,
but let's step on it...

407
00:21:56,607 --> 00:21:58,650
or the pizza's
gonna freeze, honey.

408
00:21:59,652 --> 00:22:02,779
Maybe we could all
go out sometime...

409
00:22:02,863 --> 00:22:04,447
you know,
dinner in the city.

410
00:22:04,907 --> 00:22:06,950
You would like her,
I think.

411
00:22:07,910 --> 00:22:10,745
God, remember when all you had
to do was a few buckles?

412
00:22:10,955 --> 00:22:12,580
Yep. Those
were the days.

413
00:22:13,749 --> 00:22:14,958
I called the inn.

414
00:22:15,042 --> 00:22:18,211
All they can give you is a
ground-floor single in the new wing.

415
00:22:20,256 --> 00:22:21,715
Did you tell them
it was me?

416
00:22:22,842 --> 00:22:25,093
Well... I said Parker.

417
00:22:35,146 --> 00:22:38,106
Helmut, hier ist
Katharine Parker.

418
00:22:39,734 --> 00:22:41,443
[Speaking German]

419
00:22:59,879 --> 00:23:01,296
Ciao.

420
00:23:03,466 --> 00:23:05,467
It's this tower room
with a canopy bed

421
00:23:05,551 --> 00:23:07,802
and a fireplace
big enough to stand in.

422
00:23:08,888 --> 00:23:10,430
Perfect.

423
00:23:10,514 --> 00:23:11,890
Everything's in place.

424
00:23:13,392 --> 00:23:14,476
For what?

425
00:23:15,102 --> 00:23:17,020
The man I've been
seeing for a while.

426
00:23:17,897 --> 00:23:19,898
I think he's it,

427
00:23:19,982 --> 00:23:22,942
and this could be
the weekend we decide.

428
00:23:23,027 --> 00:23:24,694
He said there was
something very important

429
00:23:24,779 --> 00:23:26,696
he wanted to discuss
with me.

430
00:23:27,281 --> 00:23:30,200
- I think he's gonna pop the question.
- You do?

431
00:23:30,284 --> 00:23:32,535
I think so.
We're in the same city.

432
00:23:32,995 --> 00:23:35,705
I've indicated
that I'm receptive to an offer,

433
00:23:35,790 --> 00:23:37,415
I've cleared June,

434
00:23:37,500 --> 00:23:39,709
and I am,
after all, me.

435
00:23:41,504 --> 00:23:44,172
Well, what if he doesn't
pop the question?

436
00:23:45,674 --> 00:23:47,759
I really don't think
that's a variable.

437
00:23:49,095 --> 00:23:50,178
Tess, you know,

438
00:23:50,262 --> 00:23:51,596
you don't get anywhere
in this world

439
00:23:51,680 --> 00:23:54,432
by waiting for what you want
to come to you.

440
00:23:55,184 --> 00:23:56,893
You make it happen.

441
00:23:57,937 --> 00:23:59,521
Watch me, Tess.

442
00:24:00,064 --> 00:24:01,564
Learn from me.

443
00:24:04,068 --> 00:24:06,986
Oh, I ran your
Trask radio idea

444
00:24:07,071 --> 00:24:08,363
by some
of our people.

445
00:24:08,697 --> 00:24:11,032
It seems Trask
is dead set on television.

446
00:24:12,368 --> 00:24:14,035
It wasn't out
in left field.

447
00:24:14,120 --> 00:24:15,578
I really
like the idea.

448
00:24:15,871 --> 00:24:18,748
Keep plugging.
Bring me your ideas.

449
00:24:18,833 --> 00:24:20,208
We'll see
what we can do.

450
00:24:21,919 --> 00:24:23,378
Thank you, Katharine.

451
00:24:23,712 --> 00:24:24,838
Tess.

452
00:24:25,673 --> 00:24:28,466
Tess, look at me.

453
00:24:28,801 --> 00:24:29,926
Who makes it happen?

454
00:24:32,596 --> 00:24:33,847
I do.

455
00:24:34,473 --> 00:24:35,723
Who does?

456
00:24:37,852 --> 00:24:39,602
I do.
I make it happen.

457
00:24:40,229 --> 00:24:43,731
That's right. Only then
do we get what we deserve.

458
00:25:00,416 --> 00:25:04,002
Aah...

